               <p>SARAH MACKEWEN. I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18320906-220-person1824">
                  John 
                  Mackewen
               <interp inst="t18320906-220-person1824" type="surname" value="Mackewen"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-220-person1824" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-220-person1824" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; he is a <rs id="t18320906-220-viclabel1246" type="occupation">horse-doctor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-220-victim1821 t18320906-220-viclabel1246"></join>; I <rs id="t18320906-220-viclabel1247" type="occupation">sell fruit in the market</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-220-victim1823 t18320906-220-viclabel1247"></join>. On the morning of the 31st of July, the prisoner came to me in <placeName id="t18320906-220-crimeloc1248">Spitalfields-market</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-220-crimeloc1248" type="placeName" value="Spitalfields-market"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-220-crimeloc1248" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-220-off1243 t18320906-220-crimeloc1248"></join>, a little before seven o'clock; he asked for a pottle of raspberries, and offered 3d. for them, which I said I could not take - he went away and came back, and told me to tie him up a pottle; while I did that, I felt his hand in my pocket - I held his hand, and said,"You little rogue, you have got your hand in my pocket:" I took it out - he had some silver in it, and some copper: I saw one half-crown - I gave him into custody; he said it was his parents' money not mine, but what his mother had given him: I had a good deal of silver in my pocket, and some half-crowns.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. Did you see his hand in your pocket? A. No, but I felt it - it was outside my pocket when I saw the half-crown in it; I cannot swear that the half-crown was not in his hand before: I did not see him with any newspapers.</p>


               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-220-person1825">
                  THOMAS 
                  STONEHOUSE
               <interp inst="t18320906-220-person1825" type="surname" value="STONEHOUSE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-220-person1825" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-220-person1825" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable H 81). I took the prisoner when the prosecutrix had hold of his hand; I found one half-crown and 1 1/2d. in his hand, and 6d. worth of half pence, and 2s. 6d. in his pocket.</p>

               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, denying that he had touched the prosecutrix's pocket; and stating that the money in his hand he had received for newspapers which he had sold in the street.</p>
